{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012BVP6JrcMfHodjfY1XoGs2","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Add edit and delete UI for theme owners\n     2→\n     3→## Context\n     4→Users can create themes but have no way to edit or delete them. The backend mutations `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already exist with proper authorization (owner-only checks), but the theme detail page has no edit or delete controls. This is a critical MVP gap — users need to be able to manage their own themes.\n     5→\n     6→## Scope\n     7→Add edit and delete functionality to the theme detail page (`/theme/[slug]`) for theme owners only. No new backend work needed — `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already handle authorization and cleanup.\n     8→\n     9→## Tasks\n    10→\n    11→### 1. Add owner detection to the theme detail page\n    12→- **File:** `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx`\n    13→- Compare the current authenticated user's ID with `theme.authorId`\n    14→- Only show edit/delete controls when the viewer is the theme owner\n    15→\n    16→### 2. Add a delete button with confirmation\n    17→- Show a \"Delete\" button (styled as a danger action) visible only to the owner\n    18→- On click, show a confirmation dialog (inline confirm/cancel, not `window.confirm`)\n    19→- On confirm, call `useMutation(api.themes.remove)` with the theme `_id`\n    20→- On success, redirect to the homepage (`/`)\n    21→- Show an error message if the mutation fails\n    22→\n    23→### 3. Add an inline edit mode for theme metadata\n    24→- Add an \"Edit\" button visible only to the owner\n    25→- Clicking \"Edit\" toggles the page into an edit mode where:\n    26→  - Theme name becomes an editable text input\n    27→  - Description becomes an editable textarea\n    28→  - Public/private becomes a toggle switch\n    29→- Show \"Save\" and \"Cancel\" buttons in edit mode\n    30→- On \"Save\", call `useMutation(api.themes.update)` with only the changed fields\n    31→- On \"Cancel\", revert to the display view without saving\n    32→- If the name changes, the slug will change server-side — after save, redirect to the new slug URL (returned from the mutation, or re-fetch)\n    33→\n    34→### 4. Add inline edit mode for colors\n    35→- In edit mode, each color swatch becomes editable\n    36→- Use color picker inputs (`<input type=\"color\">`) or hex text inputs for each color\n    37→- Pre-fill with the current values\n    38→- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n    39→\n    40→### 5. Add inline edit mode for fonts\n    41→- In edit mode, font names become editable text inputs\n    42→- Pre-fill with current values\n    43→- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n    44→\n    45→### 6. Handle edge cases\n    46→- Disable save button while mutation is in progress (prevent double-submit)\n    47→- Show loading state on save/delete buttons during mutation\n    48→- If theme is deleted by someone else while editing, handle gracefully (theme becomes null)\n    49→- Ensure the live preview panel updates in real-time as colors are edited\n    50→\n    51→## Acceptance criteria\n    52→- [ ] Edit and delete buttons only appear for the theme owner\n    53→- [ ] Delete shows inline confirmation and redirects to `/` on success\n    54→- [ ] Edit mode allows changing name, description, visibility, colors, and fonts\n    55→- [ ] Save calls `themes.update` with only changed fields and handles slug changes\n    56→- [ ] Cancel reverts all edits without calling the backend\n    57→- [ ] Live preview updates as colors are edited\n    58→- [ ] Loading/disabled states during mutations prevent double-submit\n    59→- [ ] Page is styled with Tailwind, consistent with existing detail page design\n    60→- [ ] No new backend changes or npm dependencies needed\n    61→\n    62→## Technical notes\n    63→- `themes.update` accepts partial fields — only send what changed\n    64→- `themes.update` regenerates the slug if the name changes — the response doesn't return the new slug, so after a name change, use `router.push` to navigate to the new slug (compute it client-side as lowercase-hyphenated, or re-query)\n    65→- `themes.remove` cascades deletes to all stars and comments for the theme\n    66→- The current user's ID can be obtained from the auth context already used by the star/comment features on this page\n    67→- Tailwind v4 is in use\n    68→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1ebead00-88c4-4461-9c40-1c8921dadd20","uuid":"1ddd8d84-0750-4bf1-a1b3-f377e8f01a72","timestamp":"2026-03-27T23:49:53.605Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/matt/code/themedrops/swarm/tasks/theme-edit-delete-ui.todo.md","content":"# Add edit and delete UI for theme owners\n\n## Context\nUsers can create themes but have no way to edit or delete them. The backend mutations `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already exist with proper authorization (owner-only checks), but the theme detail page has no edit or delete controls. This is a critical MVP gap — users need to be able to manage their own themes.\n\n## Scope\nAdd edit and delete functionality to the theme detail page (`/theme/[slug]`) for theme owners only. No new backend work needed — `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already handle authorization and cleanup.\n\n## Tasks\n\n### 1. Add owner detection to the theme detail page\n- **File:** `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx`\n- Compare the current authenticated user's ID with `theme.authorId`\n- Only show edit/delete controls when the viewer is the theme owner\n\n### 2. Add a delete button with confirmation\n- Show a \"Delete\" button (styled as a danger action) visible only to the owner\n- On click, show a confirmation dialog (inline confirm/cancel, not `window.confirm`)\n- On confirm, call `useMutation(api.themes.remove)` with the theme `_id`\n- On success, redirect to the homepage (`/`)\n- Show an error message if the mutation fails\n\n### 3. Add an inline edit mode for theme metadata\n- Add an \"Edit\" button visible only to the owner\n- Clicking \"Edit\" toggles the page into an edit mode where:\n  - Theme name becomes an editable text input\n  - Description becomes an editable textarea\n  - Public/private becomes a toggle switch\n- Show \"Save\" and \"Cancel\" buttons in edit mode\n- On \"Save\", call `useMutation(api.themes.update)` with only the changed fields\n- On \"Cancel\", revert to the display view without saving\n- If the name changes, the slug will change server-side — after save, redirect to the new slug URL (returned from the mutation, or re-fetch)\n\n### 4. Add inline edit mode for colors\n- In edit mode, each color swatch becomes editable\n- Use color picker inputs (`<input type=\"color\">`) or hex text inputs for each color\n- Pre-fill with the current values\n- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n\n### 5. Add inline edit mode for fonts\n- In edit mode, font names become editable text inputs\n- Pre-fill with current values\n- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n\n### 6. Handle edge cases\n- Disable save button while mutation is in progress (prevent double-submit)\n- Show loading state on save/delete buttons during mutation\n- If theme is deleted by someone else while editing, handle gracefully (theme becomes null)\n- Ensure the live preview panel updates in real-time as colors are edited\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n- [ ] Edit and delete buttons only appear for the theme owner\n- [ ] Delete shows inline confirmation and redirects to `/` on success\n- [ ] Edit mode allows changing name, description, visibility, colors, and fonts\n- [ ] Save calls `themes.update` with only changed fields and handles slug changes\n- [ ] Cancel reverts all edits without calling the backend\n- [ ] Live preview updates as colors are edited\n- [ ] Loading/disabled states during mutations prevent double-submit\n- [ ] Page is styled with Tailwind, consistent with existing detail page design\n- [ ] No new backend changes or npm dependencies needed\n\n## Technical notes\n- `themes.update` accepts partial fields — only send what changed\n- `themes.update` regenerates the slug if the name changes — the response doesn't return the new slug, so after a name change, use `router.push` to navigate to the new slug (compute it client-side as lowercase-hyphenated, or re-query)\n- `themes.remove` cascades deletes to all stars and comments for the theme\n- The current user's ID can be obtained from the auth context already used by the star/comment features on this page\n- Tailwind v4 is in use\n","numLines":68,"startLine":1,"totalLines":68}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QepHA5CjMYWnDFCGTNGf4C","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Build the theme detail page\n     2→\n     3→## Context\n     4→The backend has all the queries needed to display a single theme (`themes.getBySlug`, `comments.listByTheme`, `stars.isStarred`, `stars.toggle`), but there is no frontend page to view an individual theme. The homepage gallery (in progress) will link to theme pages by slug — without a detail page, clicking a theme card leads nowhere. This is a critical MVP gap.\n     5→\n     6→## Scope\n     7→Create a dynamic route page at `/theme/[slug]` that displays a single theme's full details, allows starring, and shows comments. No new backend queries needed — everything exists already.\n     8→\n     9→## Tasks\n    10→\n    11→### 1. Create the dynamic route page\n    12→- **File:** `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx`\n    13→- `\"use client\"` component (needs Convex hooks)\n    14→- Use `useQuery(api.themes.getBySlug, { slug })` to fetch the theme\n    15→- Extract slug from route params\n    16→\n    17→### 2. Theme detail layout\n    18→- Display the theme name prominently as a heading\n    19→- Show description below the name\n    20→- Show author display name (resolve from `authorId` via a simple query, or fetch inline)\n    21→- If the theme is a fork, show \"Forked from [original name]\" with link\n    22→- Show the theme slug for API usage reference (e.g. \"API: `/api/theme/slug-name`\")\n    23→\n    24→### 3. Color palette display\n    25→- Render all 6 color values (background, foreground, primary, secondary, accent, muted) as large swatches\n    26→- Show the hex value label under/beside each swatch\n    27→- Show a live preview panel: a small card/section styled with the theme's actual colors (background, foreground text, primary button, etc.)\n    28→- Handle missing optional colors gracefully (skip them)\n    29→\n    30→### 4. Font display\n    31→- If fonts are present, show sans/serif/mono font names\n    32→- Optionally render sample text in each font (if it's a Google Font or system font)\n    33→\n    34→### 5. Star button\n    35→- Use `useQuery(api.stars.isStarred, { themeId })` to check current star state\n    36→- Use `useMutation(api.stars.toggle)` to toggle\n    37→- Show star count from the theme object\n    38→- Display filled/unfilled star icon based on state\n    39→- Disable or hide for unauthenticated users\n    40→\n    41→### 6. Comments section\n    42→- Use `useQuery(api.comments.listByTheme, { themeId })` to fetch comments\n    43→- Display each comment with author name, body text\n    44→- If authenticated, show a text input + submit button to add a comment via `useMutation(api.comments.create)`\n    45→- Handle empty comments state (\"No comments yet\")\n    46→\n    47→### 7. Fork button\n    48→- Show a \"Fork this theme\" button for authenticated users\n    49→- Use `useMutation(api.themes.fork)`\n    50→- On success, navigate to the forked theme's page (or show a success message)\n    51→\n    52→### 8. Handle edge cases\n    53→- 404 / not found state if `getBySlug` returns null\n    54→- Loading state while data fetches\n    55→- Private theme returns null for non-owners — show appropriate message\n    56→\n    57→## Acceptance criteria\n    58→- [x] `/theme/[slug]` route renders theme details fetched from Convex (not hardcoded)\n    59→- [x] All 6 color swatches display with hex labels\n    60→- [x] Star button shows current state and toggles correctly\n    61→- [x] Comments list renders with author names\n    62→- [x] Authenticated users can add comments and fork the theme\n    63→- [x] Loading and not-found states are handled\n    64→- [x] Page is styled with Tailwind, consistent with homepage design\n    65→- [x] No new npm dependencies required\n    66→\n    67→## Technical notes\n    68→- `themes.getBySlug` already handles privacy (returns null for private themes unless viewer is the author)\n    69→- `comments.listByTheme` already resolves author info (username, displayName, avatarUrl)\n    70→- The theme `_id` is needed for stars/comments/fork mutations — get it from the `getBySlug` response\n    71→- Convex document IDs are available as `_id` on returned objects\n    72→- Tailwind v4 is in use\n    73→\n    74→## Implementation notes\n    75→- Created `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx` as a `\"use client\"` component\n    76→- Added `users.get` query to `convex/users.ts` to resolve author display name from `authorId` (returns only public fields)\n    77→- Uses `useParams` from `next/navigation` to extract the slug\n    78→- Color swatches render as 16x16 rounded squares with hex labels; missing colors are skipped\n    79→- Live preview panel shows a card styled with all theme colors (background, foreground text, primary/secondary/accent buttons)\n    80→- Font section renders sample text in each font family if fonts are present\n    81→- Star button shows filled/unfilled star with count; disabled for unauthenticated users\n    82→- Comments section shows all comments with author info; authenticated users get an inline form to post\n    83→- Fork button navigates to the new forked theme page on success\n    84→- Loading spinner and not-found states handled\n    85→- TypeScript compiles cleanly with no errors\n    86→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1ebead00-88c4-4461-9c40-1c8921dadd20","uuid":"669ce7c3-50e2-4832-b03c-570e9167861d","timestamp":"2026-03-27T23:49:53.607Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/matt/code/themedrops/swarm/tasks/theme-detail-page.reviewing.md","content":"# Build the theme detail page\n\n## Context\nThe backend has all the queries needed to display a single theme (`themes.getBySlug`, `comments.listByTheme`, `stars.isStarred`, `stars.toggle`), but there is no frontend page to view an individual theme. The homepage gallery (in progress) will link to theme pages by slug — without a detail page, clicking a theme card leads nowhere. This is a critical MVP gap.\n\n## Scope\nCreate a dynamic route page at `/theme/[slug]` that displays a single theme's full details, allows starring, and shows comments. No new backend queries needed — everything exists already.\n\n## Tasks\n\n### 1. Create the dynamic route page\n- **File:** `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx`\n- `\"use client\"` component (needs Convex hooks)\n- Use `useQuery(api.themes.getBySlug, { slug })` to fetch the theme\n- Extract slug from route params\n\n### 2. Theme detail layout\n- Display the theme name prominently as a heading\n- Show description below the name\n- Show author display name (resolve from `authorId` via a simple query, or fetch inline)\n- If the theme is a fork, show \"Forked from [original name]\" with link\n- Show the theme slug for API usage reference (e.g. \"API: `/api/theme/slug-name`\")\n\n### 3. Color palette display\n- Render all 6 color values (background, foreground, primary, secondary, accent, muted) as large swatches\n- Show the hex value label under/beside each swatch\n- Show a live preview panel: a small card/section styled with the theme's actual colors (background, foreground text, primary button, etc.)\n- Handle missing optional colors gracefully (skip them)\n\n### 4. Font display\n- If fonts are present, show sans/serif/mono font names\n- Optionally render sample text in each font (if it's a Google Font or system font)\n\n### 5. Star button\n- Use `useQuery(api.stars.isStarred, { themeId })` to check current star state\n- Use `useMutation(api.stars.toggle)` to toggle\n- Show star count from the theme object\n- Display filled/unfilled star icon based on state\n- Disable or hide for unauthenticated users\n\n### 6. Comments section\n- Use `useQuery(api.comments.listByTheme, { themeId })` to fetch comments\n- Display each comment with author name, body text\n- If authenticated, show a text input + submit button to add a comment via `useMutation(api.comments.create)`\n- Handle empty comments state (\"No comments yet\")\n\n### 7. Fork button\n- Show a \"Fork this theme\" button for authenticated users\n- Use `useMutation(api.themes.fork)`\n- On success, navigate to the forked theme's page (or show a success message)\n\n### 8. Handle edge cases\n- 404 / not found state if `getBySlug` returns null\n- Loading state while data fetches\n- Private theme returns null for non-owners — show appropriate message\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n- [x] `/theme/[slug]` route renders theme details fetched from Convex (not hardcoded)\n- [x] All 6 color swatches display with hex labels\n- [x] Star button shows current state and toggles correctly\n- [x] Comments list renders with author names\n- [x] Authenticated users can add comments and fork the theme\n- [x] Loading and not-found states are handled\n- [x] Page is styled with Tailwind, consistent with homepage design\n- [x] No new npm dependencies required\n\n## Technical notes\n- `themes.getBySlug` already handles privacy (returns null for private themes unless viewer is the author)\n- `comments.listByTheme` already resolves author info (username, displayName, avatarUrl)\n- The theme `_id` is needed for stars/comments/fork mutations — get it from the `getBySlug` response\n- Convex document IDs are available as `_id` on returned objects\n- Tailwind v4 is in use\n\n## Implementation notes\n- Created `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx` as a `\"use client\"` component\n- Added `users.get` query to `convex/users.ts` to resolve author display name from `authorId` (returns only public fields)\n- Uses `useParams` from `next/navigation` to extract the slug\n- Color swatches render as 16x16 rounded squares with hex labels; missing colors are skipped\n- Live preview panel shows a card styled with all theme colors (background, foreground text, primary/secondary/accent buttons)\n- Font section renders sample text in each font family if fonts are present\n- Star button shows filled/unfilled star with count; disabled for unauthenticated users\n- Comments section shows all comments with author info; authenticated users get an inline form to post\n- Fork button navigates to the new forked theme page on success\n- Loading spinner and not-found states handled\n- TypeScript compiles cleanly with no errors\n","numLines":86,"startLine":1,"totalLines":86}}}
