{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HA6ZCyhNwYPyACXdo4pkQF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Add edit and delete UI for theme owners\n     2→\n     3→## Context\n     4→Users can create themes but have no way to edit or delete them. The backend mutations `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already exist with proper authorization (owner-only checks), but the theme detail page has no edit or delete controls. This is a critical MVP gap — users need to be able to manage their own themes.\n     5→\n     6→## Scope\n     7→Add edit and delete functionality to the theme detail page (`/theme/[slug]`) for theme owners only. No new backend work needed — `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already handle authorization and cleanup.\n     8→\n     9→## Tasks\n    10→\n    11→### 1. Add owner detection to the theme detail page\n    12→- **File:** `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx`\n    13→- Compare the current authenticated user's ID with `theme.authorId`\n    14→- Only show edit/delete controls when the viewer is the theme owner\n    15→\n    16→### 2. Add a delete button with confirmation\n    17→- Show a \"Delete\" button (styled as a danger action) visible only to the owner\n    18→- On click, show a confirmation dialog (inline confirm/cancel, not `window.confirm`)\n    19→- On confirm, call `useMutation(api.themes.remove)` with the theme `_id`\n    20→- On success, redirect to the homepage (`/`)\n    21→- Show an error message if the mutation fails\n    22→\n    23→### 3. Add an inline edit mode for theme metadata\n    24→- Add an \"Edit\" button visible only to the owner\n    25→- Clicking \"Edit\" toggles the page into an edit mode where:\n    26→  - Theme name becomes an editable text input\n    27→  - Description becomes an editable textarea\n    28→  - Public/private becomes a toggle switch\n    29→- Show \"Save\" and \"Cancel\" buttons in edit mode\n    30→- On \"Save\", call `useMutation(api.themes.update)` with only the changed fields\n    31→- On \"Cancel\", revert to the display view without saving\n    32→- If the name changes, the slug will change server-side — after save, redirect to the new slug URL (returned from the mutation, or re-fetch)\n    33→\n    34→### 4. Add inline edit mode for colors\n    35→- In edit mode, each color swatch becomes editable\n    36→- Use color picker inputs (`<input type=\"color\">`) or hex text inputs for each color\n    37→- Pre-fill with the current values\n    38→- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n    39→\n    40→### 5. Add inline edit mode for fonts\n    41→- In edit mode, font names become editable text inputs\n    42→- Pre-fill with current values\n    43→- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n    44→\n    45→### 6. Handle edge cases\n    46→- Disable save button while mutation is in progress (prevent double-submit)\n    47→- Show loading state on save/delete buttons during mutation\n    48→- If theme is deleted by someone else while editing, handle gracefully (theme becomes null)\n    49→- Ensure the live preview panel updates in real-time as colors are edited\n    50→\n    51→## Acceptance criteria\n    52→- [ ] Edit and delete buttons only appear for the theme owner\n    53→- [ ] Delete shows inline confirmation and redirects to `/` on success\n    54→- [ ] Edit mode allows changing name, description, visibility, colors, and fonts\n    55→- [ ] Save calls `themes.update` with only changed fields and handles slug changes\n    56→- [ ] Cancel reverts all edits without calling the backend\n    57→- [ ] Live preview updates as colors are edited\n    58→- [ ] Loading/disabled states during mutations prevent double-submit\n    59→- [ ] Page is styled with Tailwind, consistent with existing detail page design\n    60→- [ ] No new backend changes or npm dependencies needed\n    61→\n    62→## Technical notes\n    63→- `themes.update` accepts partial fields — only send what changed\n    64→- `themes.update` regenerates the slug if the name changes — the response doesn't return the new slug, so after a name change, use `router.push` to navigate to the new slug (compute it client-side as lowercase-hyphenated, or re-query)\n    65→- `themes.remove` cascades deletes to all stars and comments for the theme\n    66→- The current user's ID can be obtained from the auth context already used by the star/comment features on this page\n    67→- Tailwind v4 is in use\n    68→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1ebead00-88c4-4461-9c40-1c8921dadd20","uuid":"305be61b-3cfa-44d3-9b75-8efc0884c3ef","timestamp":"2026-03-27T23:52:44.197Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/matt/code/themedrops/swarm/tasks/theme-edit-delete-ui.processing.md","content":"# Add edit and delete UI for theme owners\n\n## Context\nUsers can create themes but have no way to edit or delete them. The backend mutations `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already exist with proper authorization (owner-only checks), but the theme detail page has no edit or delete controls. This is a critical MVP gap — users need to be able to manage their own themes.\n\n## Scope\nAdd edit and delete functionality to the theme detail page (`/theme/[slug]`) for theme owners only. No new backend work needed — `themes.update` and `themes.remove` already handle authorization and cleanup.\n\n## Tasks\n\n### 1. Add owner detection to the theme detail page\n- **File:** `app/src/app/theme/[slug]/page.tsx`\n- Compare the current authenticated user's ID with `theme.authorId`\n- Only show edit/delete controls when the viewer is the theme owner\n\n### 2. Add a delete button with confirmation\n- Show a \"Delete\" button (styled as a danger action) visible only to the owner\n- On click, show a confirmation dialog (inline confirm/cancel, not `window.confirm`)\n- On confirm, call `useMutation(api.themes.remove)` with the theme `_id`\n- On success, redirect to the homepage (`/`)\n- Show an error message if the mutation fails\n\n### 3. Add an inline edit mode for theme metadata\n- Add an \"Edit\" button visible only to the owner\n- Clicking \"Edit\" toggles the page into an edit mode where:\n  - Theme name becomes an editable text input\n  - Description becomes an editable textarea\n  - Public/private becomes a toggle switch\n- Show \"Save\" and \"Cancel\" buttons in edit mode\n- On \"Save\", call `useMutation(api.themes.update)` with only the changed fields\n- On \"Cancel\", revert to the display view without saving\n- If the name changes, the slug will change server-side — after save, redirect to the new slug URL (returned from the mutation, or re-fetch)\n\n### 4. Add inline edit mode for colors\n- In edit mode, each color swatch becomes editable\n- Use color picker inputs (`<input type=\"color\">`) or hex text inputs for each color\n- Pre-fill with the current values\n- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n\n### 5. Add inline edit mode for fonts\n- In edit mode, font names become editable text inputs\n- Pre-fill with current values\n- Include in the save payload sent to `themes.update`\n\n### 6. Handle edge cases\n- Disable save button while mutation is in progress (prevent double-submit)\n- Show loading state on save/delete buttons during mutation\n- If theme is deleted by someone else while editing, handle gracefully (theme becomes null)\n- Ensure the live preview panel updates in real-time as colors are edited\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n- [ ] Edit and delete buttons only appear for the theme owner\n- [ ] Delete shows inline confirmation and redirects to `/` on success\n- [ ] Edit mode allows changing name, description, visibility, colors, and fonts\n- [ ] Save calls `themes.update` with only changed fields and handles slug changes\n- [ ] Cancel reverts all edits without calling the backend\n- [ ] Live preview updates as colors are edited\n- [ ] Loading/disabled states during mutations prevent double-submit\n- [ ] Page is styled with Tailwind, consistent with existing detail page design\n- [ ] No new backend changes or npm dependencies needed\n\n## Technical notes\n- `themes.update` accepts partial fields — only send what changed\n- `themes.update` regenerates the slug if the name changes — the response doesn't return the new slug, so after a name change, use `router.push` to navigate to the new slug (compute it client-side as lowercase-hyphenated, or re-query)\n- `themes.remove` cascades deletes to all stars and comments for the theme\n- The current user's ID can be obtained from the auth context already used by the star/comment features on this page\n- Tailwind v4 is in use\n","numLines":68,"startLine":1,"totalLines":68}}}
